 views of the natural world. Broad in scope, clearly written, and at the center of current scholarly debates, Working the Diaspora challenges readers to alter their conceptual frameworks about Africans by looking at them as workers who, through the course of the Atlantic slave trade and plantation labor, shaped the development of the Americas in significant ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aAfricanszAmericaxHistory. 0aAgricultural laborerszAmericaxHistory. 0aAgriculturezAmericaxHistory. 0aBlack peoplezAmericaxHistory. 0aBlackszAmericaxHistory. 0aSlave laborzAmericaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh  aAfricans.  aAmericas.  aAtlantic.  aBroad.  aDiaspora.  aWorking.  aabout.  aalter.  acenter.  achallenges.  aclearly.  aconceptual.  acourse.  acurrent.  adebates.  adevelopment.  aframeworks.  alabor.  alooking.  aplantation.  areaders.  ascholarly.  ascope.  ashaped.  asignificant.  aslave.  atheir.  athem.  athrough.  atrade.  aways.  awho.  aworkers.  awritten.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814748183.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814749128zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814749128/original  a978-3-11-070644-4 New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA